In mean-field hydrodynamics, the components of the Reynolds stress which transfer angular momentum are typically represented in terms of a diffusive contribution represented by an anisotropic turbulent viscosity νt and a non-diffusive contribution known as the Λ-effect [Equation (23)]. These two contributions are generally comparable in amplitude so the relative strength of the Coriolis force and the Reynolds stress may be quantified by the Taylor number based on the turbulent viscosity: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
